rComments: Dr. Zakzanis is the epitome of what a UofT professor should be: inspiring, persuasive, entertaining, passionate, always couches opinion in terms of evidence based research literature, dedicated to ensuring student understanding of complex course topics. I hung on to every word even though the lectures were 3 hours in duration.

Zakzanis is one of my absolute favorite profsl! Even if a course's content is more challenging to learn and internalize, I always look forward to attending his classes because of how engaging and entertaining he is. The anecdotes he uses with his dog are memorable too. As a prof he is approachable, clearly understandable, and supportive. A for him.
Gives us an idea of how things work in the real world and gives us confidence
Amazing teacher :) Loved his course!! Would def take more courses with him.

Honestly he is one of my favourite professors as he is inspirational and an amazing lecturer. His exams are mostly based on lectures but skimming the textbook is also helpful as both are fair game. I would say go to lectures in person (if the option is available). All in all, amazing prof and fair exams. PS- the TAs can be a little tough on grading
Loved this course! Dr. Zakzanis is an amazing lecturer, he explains the material really well, he's also a really nice guy. Exams were mainly lecture based.

Prof. Zakzanis is a very knowledgable guy, and makes his evening classes very enjoyable. The midterms were both very fair (make sure to write down lecture notes AND read the textbook) and the assignments were pretty straight forward (follow the rubric). Love Zakzanis but the way he pronounces "allele" is a no from me omg LOL

This course really helps you understand psychological disorders and their real world context. The concepts are incredibly interesting and Prof. Z makes them come to life. If you have the option of in person or online lectures, definitely go in person. Will definitely be taking courses with him in the future if possible. Highly recommend this class!

Amazing prof with super engaging, personable lectures. He doesn't just read off the slides and seems genuinely interested in what he's teaching. The assessments are quite easy and there isn't much work throughout the term. Had a great semester with him and would love for him to be my professor again!
Amazing professor, who not only teaches what's required in the syllabus but also things that will help you improve as a person. Would highly recommend even if you're not in mental health/psych.

He is an amazing lecturer who is able to relate real life situations to the course concept. Take this class irrespective of the fact its a requirement for your programme or not. Plus his exams are fair to lecture content and textbook too. Additionally, the tas are pretty brutual in marking the assignement. You have to work hard to earn that A+.

I sacrificed my summer evenings for this class and did not regret it at all! Prof Zakzanis was an amazing lecturer, and hilarious! The course material was extremely interesting. Just like any course, if you study, youll do well. The exams were fair and the assignment was simple! I highly recommend this course even if you dont need it!

He is an amazing lecturer. Loves to give real life examples concerning to concepts taught in class. hard to get 85 and above. You have to put work in it for that A. rComments: literally one of the most interesting and well taught courses. the prof makes the content sound very very interesting and he is humorous&very nice and easy to approach and interact with. would definitely recommend taking PSYB32 if u are majoring in psych. rComments: It's harder to fail this course than it is to pass with an A. To do well, you have to read the material. If you got a low mark it is because you didn't read the textbook, which is a mistake. The lectures are great but you'll do poorly if you rely on just that. Why should the prof read the material when it's supposed to be us doing the learning?

I'm weboptioning this course this winter semester but I wish I could have taken it in person. I love his lectures, they're always so engaging and interesting to watch.
